observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to ensure: 

 The immediate liquidation of cash advances  to avoid the accumulation of the balance of the account;

That the Municipal Accountant enforce the “Certification from the Accountant that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books” as a documentary requirement before a new cash advance is granted;

That the granting of cash advances to elective officials aside from their travelling expenses be stopped; 

That the Municipal Accountant require a copy of the approved application for bond before allowing the disbursement of cash advances to special disbursing officers; and 

That the Municipal Treasurer collect the overpayment of travelling expenses from the concerned officials and employees amounting to ₱23,850.00.

We have recommended that Municipal Mayor require:

the Contractor of Package 2017-48: Core Local Access Road Amganad to rectify the minor cracks at Sta. 0+043 and Sta. 0+162 under Item Part B.7; and

the Municipal Engineer to – 

compute for the liquidated damages on the two (2) delayed projects as noted by the COA CAR  STAS, then recoup the amount from the contractor;

provide complete data, i.e. contract duration and percentage of accomplishment on the date of contract expiry;

We have recommended and management agreed to:
review and re-evaluate, thru the Municipal Development Council and the Municipal Engineering Office, the unimplemented projects whether these are still considered as priority projects and are relevant and responsive to the needs of the constituents and whether the appropriations are still enough considering inflation;
revert the appropriations of the projects that are no longer feasible for implementation based on the review and re-evaluation of PPAs including the unexpended balances of completed projects for re-appropriation for other priority development projects;
Monitor and evaluate regularly the implementation of projects, through the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator, as basis in taking immediate appropriate action for the timely completion of projects; and
henceforth, implement duly funded projects within schedule to immediately address the needs and aspirations of the people.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

record ND No. 2010-001-100(2009) with NFD amounting to ₱187,500.00;

prepare adjusting entry to transfer the unliquidated cash advances amounting to ₱133,063.00 under the Disallowances and Charges account to Other Receivables account; and

We have recommended that Management:

maintain property cards with complete and updated data for each PPE item of the Municipality - Property Stock Cards for the Property Officer and Property Ledger Cards for the Municipal Accountant;

expedite the preparation of the CY2017 RPCPPE by conducting physical count of all PPE items, using the data already gathered as benchmark, and continue preparing annual RPCPPE;

thereafter, reconcile records between the Property Custodian and the Municipal Accountant; 

submit the RPCPPE to COA not later than January 31 of each year.

We have recommended that Management:

submit the enumerated CY 2017 vouchers soonest; 

require the Municipal Engineer to submit the Consolidated Quarterly Report of Government Projects/Programs/ Activities not later than the 20th day after the end of the quarter.

We have recommended that Management:

henceforth, serve written reminders/ demand letters to officials, employees and those not anymore connected with the MLGU with outstanding cash advances, to settle immediately, or else, resort to withholding of any money due them and/or impose sanctions, when necessary;

discontinue the practice of partial liquidation of cash advances;

enforce submission of complete documentary requirements in the granting and liquidation of cash advances, i.e. RODs, LVs, ObR, list of payees, estimate of expenses, etc.;

henceforth, require the prompt liquidation of all cash advances.

We have recommended and Management agreed to comply with Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002.  Further, we have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

grant cash advance to officers and employees after liquidation and accounting of previous cash advances;

require a Certification from the Accountant that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books to support a subsequent cash advance;

exert extra efforts to cause the immediate liquidation of cash advances totaling P1,026,071.52  pursuant to Section 8, COA Circular No. 97-02; and

submit justification for the cash advances totaling P269,831.96, which were utilized for other purposes, and ensure that cash advances are used solely for the specific purpose for which they were granted.

We have recommended and the Management agreed to:

submit to the Audit Team the Office Order or its equivalent authorizing the its personnel to report for work during the ECQ to establish validity of the claims as required by DBM Budget Circular No. 2020-1;

comply with Section 4.5 of PD No. 1445;

henceforth, ensure that all future claims must be supported with complete documentation in conformity with COA Circular No. 2012-001, as well as ; and

require the 26 concerned personnel to refund the excess payment of COVID-19 Hazard pay totaling P15,750.00.

We have recommended that Management:

include both the list of projects and activities charged to the current and unexpended previous years’ LDRRMF in the LDRRMFIP ensuring that each line item shall correspond to a specific purpose and amount;

fast track the implementation of the 51 unimplemented LDRRMF projects and activities totaling ₱4,441,542.98;



require the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer and the Municipal Engineer to closely monitor the implementation and accomplishment of the LDRRMFIP of the Municipality; and

require the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to submit the required monthly report on the receipt and utilization of the LDRRMF sourced from appropriations.

We have recommended that:

the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer reconcile their cash balances periodically, by tracing the causes of the discrepancies and effecting the necessary adjustments to ensure completeness and accuracy of the recorded transactions and the balance of cash in bank; 

Management to comply with the DOF Circulars by transferring soonest its two (2) accounts from PNB - Lagawe Branch to LBP - Lagawe Branch or other AGDBs.

We have reiterated our recommendations that Management:

strictly adopt the “no liquidation, no cash advance” policy;




enforce submission of Certification from the Accountant that previous cash advances have been liquidated and accounted for in the books before a new cash advance is granted (except for travels);

discontinue granting cash advance for operating expenses to ineligible employees or those not considered as AOs;

refrain from resorting to procurement through cash advances, unless justifiable; and

through the Municipal Treasurer, submit to the Municipal Accountant all liquidation vouchers and payrolls as soon as these are disbursed, and the latter to record the liquidation promptly, in order to reflect the correct account balances in the correct accounting period.

We have recommended that Management, henceforth:

clearly provide qualitative and quantitative data that would support the gender issues identified in the GPB, especially if the PPA is intended to be a GAD-focused activity taking 100% of its allocation from GAD;

administer the HGDG test on the GAD PPAs in the preparation of GPB and AR, as basis for determining the actual expenditure that can be attributed to the GAD Budget;

if and when necessary, conduct a training program on the HGDG for the incoming year and seek assistance of a gender analysis expert in the use of and/administration of the HGDG.

We have recommended that Management:

complete the tax mapping operations by providing adequate funds, modern equipment, manpower and other needed support, to come up with reliable RPT records that will establish a permanent link between the real properties in the field and the property assessment and tax records in the office;

thereafter, ensure that reports submitted to the Municipal Treasurer, which are forwarded to the Municipal Accountant, are accurate and reliable so that the tax burden will be distributed equitably, and proper accounting thereof be established.

We have recommended that Management:

require the contractors to post Performance Security, in whatever form, with validity period covering contract signing until date of Final Acceptance;

require the contractors to post Warranty Security, in whatever form, as required in the Act;

strengthen the monitoring and inspection mechanisms of the LGU, and proceed with the issuance of the Certificate of Completion after thorough evaluation of the projects as required, and the Certificate of Final Acceptance after one (1) year from date of CoC to cover the Defects Liability Period; and

make officials concerned liable incase defects are detected in projects not imposed with required warranties, and where contractors refuse to rectify.

We have recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

set-up/maintain a special account in the GF for the 20% DF;

provide a separate set of subsidiary ledgers for the special account;

prepare the corresponding financial statements to form part of the schedules of the GF trial balance; and

coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer and Sangguniang Bayan for the opening of a separate depository account for this special fund.

